1
00:00:01,750 --> 00:00:04,250
(flames roar)

2
00:00:18,383 --> 00:00:21,800
(gentle whimsical music)

3
00:02:49,077 --> 00:02:50,877
- [Penny] All my memories begin here

4
00:02:51,810 --> 00:02:54,600
in the pages of my sister's book.

5
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:57,510
Looking back, I remember
how Mary filled it

6
00:02:57,510 --> 00:03:01,293
with laughter, smiles, and magic,

7
00:03:02,190 --> 00:03:04,770
but I didn't understand any of that.

8
00:03:04,770 --> 00:03:06,423
I only believed in forgetting,

9
00:03:07,410 --> 00:03:11,583
until Mary taught me how to
turn the pages of my own life.

10
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:19,578
- [Mary] Oh, look. You're awake.

11
00:03:19,578 --> 00:03:21,660
(Penny groans)

12
00:03:21,660 --> 00:03:23,250
- Damn it.

13
00:03:23,250 --> 00:03:25,350
- Doesn't anyone say good morning anymore?

14
00:03:26,400 --> 00:03:28,983
- Good morning. Damn it.

15
00:03:29,971 --> 00:03:31,638
- Good morning back.

16
00:03:33,667 --> 00:03:36,250
(gentle music)

17
00:03:48,033 --> 00:03:51,570
- [Penny] Hey, Mary. Your
book's looking really good.

18
00:03:51,570 --> 00:03:53,820
- [Mary] I worked on it all night.

19
00:03:53,820 --> 00:03:55,053
- How was your date?

20
00:03:57,120 --> 00:03:57,953
- We didn't go.

21
00:03:59,700 --> 00:04:03,723
- [Penny] He didn't take
you to France? Cheapskate.

22
00:04:05,010 --> 00:04:06,300
- I couldn't get my face right.

23
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:07,773
- [Penny] Oh, thank you.

24
00:04:10,740 --> 00:04:12,360
Oh, that feels so good.

25
00:04:17,057 --> 00:04:19,233
- Penny, what did you do to yourself?

26
00:04:20,550 --> 00:04:23,703
You slept for hours and hours,
and I couldn't wake you up.

27
00:04:27,480 --> 00:04:29,430
- I must be coming down with something.

28
00:04:31,230 --> 00:04:32,160
- You wouldn't talk to me.

29
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:33,960
It was like you didn't recognize me.

30
00:04:37,126 --> 00:04:38,970
- [Penny] Hey, hey, Miss Mary Mack,

31
00:04:38,970 --> 00:04:41,523
don't you worry about a
thing, 'cause I'm fine now.

32
00:04:43,350 --> 00:04:45,454
Can I make it up to you?

33
00:04:45,454 --> 00:04:48,121
- You don't have to do anything.

34
00:04:52,810 --> 00:04:55,393
(gentle whimsical accordion music)

35
00:04:58,518 --> 00:05:02,518
(muffled singing)

36
00:05:20,292 --> 00:05:21,459
- You thirsty?

37
00:06:07,472 --> 00:06:09,972
(Mary coughs)

38
00:06:12,489 --> 00:06:14,112
- You're getting too big for this.

39
00:06:14,112 --> 00:06:14,945
- [Mary] No, I'm not.

40
00:06:14,945 --> 00:06:17,400
I'm three years stilted in my growth.

41
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:20,910
- Stunted. And who told you that?

42
00:06:20,910 --> 00:06:22,863
- Nobody. I read it on a chart.

43
00:06:24,450 --> 00:06:26,370
Guess what just happened?

44
00:06:26,370 --> 00:06:28,137
- What just happened?

45
00:06:28,137 --> 00:06:29,283
- I'm not telling.

46
00:06:30,612 --> 00:06:34,112
(Penny and Mary giggling)

47
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:41,763
Professor's mad at you.

48
00:06:42,750 --> 00:06:43,653
- That's new.

49
00:06:45,060 --> 00:06:45,963
Are you mad at me?

50
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:49,043
Good.

51
00:06:51,690 --> 00:06:53,948
- Don't go out tonight.
Come to dinner with us.

52
00:06:53,948 --> 00:06:55,140
(Penny sighs)

53
00:06:55,140 --> 00:06:56,523
You said you'd do anything.

54
00:06:58,170 --> 00:06:59,220
- How was the clinic?

55
00:07:02,670 --> 00:07:04,380
- Rescheduled.

56
00:07:04,380 --> 00:07:06,450
- [Penny] That's new too.

57
00:07:06,450 --> 00:07:07,353
- So you'll come?

58
00:07:09,270 --> 00:07:10,470
I'll tell you my secret.

59
00:07:11,310 --> 00:07:13,890
- What, and listen to
four hours of the gospel

60
00:07:13,890 --> 00:07:15,120
according to Professor?

61
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:16,320
- Penny.

62
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:17,493
- I said I'd go.

63
00:07:20,190 --> 00:07:21,390
Now you owe me a secret.

64
00:07:23,670 --> 00:07:26,397
- Okay, ask me, "What just happened?"

65
00:07:27,690 --> 00:07:29,163
- What just happened?

66
00:07:33,236 --> 00:07:34,403
- Not telling.

67
00:07:38,913 --> 00:07:41,830
(muffled giggling)

68
00:08:11,940 --> 00:08:12,773
- Okay. Rinse.

69
00:08:21,090 --> 00:08:23,700
- I had a dream about you last night.

70
00:08:23,700 --> 00:08:26,850
- You did? What, that I was in a coma.

71
00:08:26,850 --> 00:08:29,910
- No. I don't wanna tell you.

72
00:08:29,910 --> 00:08:31,650
I'm afraid you'll think it's stupid.

73
00:08:31,650 --> 00:08:33,483
- You won't tell me anything today.

74
00:08:34,890 --> 00:08:36,183
I promise I won't laugh.

75
00:08:41,580 --> 00:08:44,823
- Well, I was looking at this star.

76
00:08:46,020 --> 00:08:47,403
I guess it was a sun.

77
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:52,740
It was shining down on a
paper forest of paper trees

78
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:54,093
and paper flowers.

79
00:08:55,170 --> 00:08:56,553
We were laying in a field.

80
00:08:57,540 --> 00:08:59,820
And you said you liked these flowers,

81
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:01,353
because they wouldn't die,

82
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:05,163
but I said that's why they're ugly.

83
00:09:06,054 --> 00:09:08,887
(whimsical music)

84
00:09:38,290 --> 00:09:42,870
- [Professor] You know, I could
have had children of my own

85
00:09:42,870 --> 00:09:45,330
if I wanted to be treated this way.

86
00:09:45,330 --> 00:09:46,800
- I told you.

87
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:47,970
- [Professor] Mm.

88
00:09:47,970 --> 00:09:51,090
This is my mother's recipe.

89
00:09:51,090 --> 00:09:54,030
Please don't offend her by not eating any.

90
00:09:54,030 --> 00:09:58,380
- Please tell Professor, that I'm sick.

91
00:09:58,380 --> 00:10:01,260
He doesn't believe me.
Maybe he'll believe you.

92
00:10:01,260 --> 00:10:02,163
- Penny's sick.

93
00:10:03,060 --> 00:10:04,860
- [Professor] Should I lecture
you about your lifestyle?

94
00:10:04,860 --> 00:10:08,133
- [Penny] No. Anyway, I was working.

95
00:10:08,970 --> 00:10:11,220
- [Mary] They always keep her so late.

96
00:10:11,220 --> 00:10:13,413
I wish you'd find a job closer to home.

97
00:10:15,630 --> 00:10:17,730
Professor's mad because
his disability check

98
00:10:17,730 --> 00:10:19,140
was stolen today.

99
00:10:19,140 --> 00:10:20,133
- It's tragic.

100
00:10:21,150 --> 00:10:24,690
- [Professor] Very tragic, but
not as tragic as your life.

101
00:10:24,690 --> 00:10:28,025
- [Penny] Don't start in on me, please.

102
00:10:28,025 --> 00:10:29,910
- Eros and Psyche.

103
00:10:29,910 --> 00:10:31,170
- [Mary] Eros and Psyche?

104
00:10:31,170 --> 00:10:32,730
- [Professor] Mm.
- Oh no.

105
00:10:32,730 --> 00:10:35,250
- [Professor] The myth of
Psyche speaks of the journey

106
00:10:35,250 --> 00:10:36,510
of the human soul,

107
00:10:36,510 --> 00:10:38,370
purified by suffering a misfortune

108
00:10:38,370 --> 00:10:43,370
until finally, it achieves
perfect happiness.

109
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:45,603
- Sounds wonderful.

110
00:10:47,880 --> 00:10:50,880
- Mary, do you think that Psyche

111
00:10:50,880 --> 00:10:55,020
could possibly be a hero of your sister's?

112
00:10:55,020 --> 00:10:58,020
- [Penny] Do you think you
could possibly kiss my ass?

113
00:10:58,020 --> 00:10:58,853
- [Professor] How articulate.

114
00:10:58,853 --> 00:11:00,603
- I know. Let's nobody fight, okay?

115
00:11:07,981 --> 00:11:09,270
- [Professor] It's a shame, you know?

116
00:11:09,270 --> 00:11:12,123
This attitude of yours.

117
00:11:14,010 --> 00:11:16,350
You were such a brilliant girl.

118
00:11:16,350 --> 00:11:21,350
So hot, and determined to
take care of everything.

119
00:11:23,070 --> 00:11:24,573
- I take care of Mary.

120
00:11:28,680 --> 00:11:32,340
- But I felt sure you'd be smart enough

121
00:11:32,340 --> 00:11:34,743
to learn how to take
care of yourself as well.

122
00:11:35,640 --> 00:11:38,633
- [Penny] And that you were
just the man to teach me. Right?

123
00:11:42,420 --> 00:11:45,173
- There's so many other ways
you could be earning a living.

124
00:11:51,060 --> 00:11:52,743
- That's my business.

125
00:11:56,811 --> 00:11:57,810
- [Reporter] Between
representatives of those countries

126
00:11:57,810 --> 00:11:59,460
and Iraqi ministers.

127
00:11:59,460 --> 00:12:00,690
Pat?

128
00:12:00,690 --> 00:12:01,530
- [Reporter] Good evening everyone.

129
00:12:01,530 --> 00:12:04,170
Our top story: the
unthinkable happened today

130
00:12:04,170 --> 00:12:05,003
after the launch

131
00:12:05,003 --> 00:12:08,220
of the highly anticipated
Ulysses one spacecraft,

132
00:12:08,220 --> 00:12:10,140
the first manned flight to explore-

133
00:12:10,140 --> 00:12:13,440
- You think Mary doesn't
know your business?

134
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:14,523
- I know you do.

135
00:12:17,040 --> 00:12:18,420
- [Reporter] Relies on the sun

136
00:12:18,420 --> 00:12:20,490
for its massive gravitational pull,

137
00:12:20,490 --> 00:12:22,443
precise navigation is critical.

138
00:12:23,370 --> 00:12:26,067
And this is where Ulysses
one's difficulties begin.

139
00:12:26,067 --> 00:12:28,920
- I worry about you.

140
00:12:28,920 --> 00:12:31,860
- Just drop it or we're leaving. Okay?

141
00:12:31,860 --> 00:12:34,260
- [Reporter] Were disrupted
by a coronal mass...

142
00:12:35,406 --> 00:12:37,380
And emergency repair was deemed essential.

143
00:12:37,380 --> 00:12:41,673
- What happens to you?

144
00:12:43,852 --> 00:12:44,685
When Mary?

145
00:12:47,519 --> 00:12:49,383
- When Mary what?

146
00:12:49,383 --> 00:12:51,753
- When Mary is gone, dear.

147
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:55,200
- [Reporter] Have termed, "Horrifying."

148
00:12:59,040 --> 00:13:01,090
- [Penny] Honey, come on, we're gonna go.

149
00:13:02,010 --> 00:13:02,933
- [Professor] Mary.

150
00:13:11,880 --> 00:13:13,557
You will love this.

151
00:13:18,019 --> 00:13:19,620
There.

152
00:13:19,620 --> 00:13:22,023
There's plenty of romance.

153
00:13:24,330 --> 00:13:25,163
- Come on.

154
00:13:25,163 --> 00:13:26,180
- Thank you Professor.

155
00:13:31,375 --> 00:13:32,720
- You're welcome.

156
00:13:32,720 --> 00:13:33,870
- [Reporter] If its
trajectory is not corrected,

157
00:13:33,870 --> 00:13:36,070
the capsule could drift
through space for...

158
00:13:37,203 --> 00:13:39,870
(eerie ringing)

159
00:13:50,911 --> 00:13:53,578
(Mary coughing)

160
00:13:54,520 --> 00:13:56,070
- You need help, sweetheart?

161
00:13:56,070 --> 00:13:57,420
- [Mary] No, I'm all right.

162
00:14:04,980 --> 00:14:07,730
Look what came in the mail
today. You should read this.

163
00:14:08,760 --> 00:14:10,020
- What is it?

164
00:14:10,020 --> 00:14:12,603
- A letter. It's from prison.

165
00:14:13,477 --> 00:14:15,303
Open it and see if it's a killer.

166
00:14:26,430 --> 00:14:27,870
- Figures.

167
00:14:27,870 --> 00:14:29,124
- What?

168
00:14:29,124 --> 00:14:30,720
- [Penny] It's about my book.

169
00:14:30,720 --> 00:14:32,850
- [Mary] Wait, I wanted to read that.

170
00:14:32,850 --> 00:14:35,750
- [Penny] What? So I can hear
about what a nice man he is.

171
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:38,580
I'm not interested in
some convict's opinion

172
00:14:38,580 --> 00:14:41,103
of my poetry of 10 years ago.

173
00:14:43,920 --> 00:14:46,650
Penny, turn out the light.

174
00:15:01,440 --> 00:15:04,844
(gentle music)

175
00:15:04,844 --> 00:15:07,344
- [Penny] Where are you going?

176
00:15:10,181 --> 00:15:11,764
What are you doing?

177
00:15:22,147 --> 00:15:26,493
- [Man] "Dear Penny, I
know this sounds crazy.

178
00:15:27,420 --> 00:15:29,013
Maybe even a little scary.

179
00:15:30,630 --> 00:15:33,483
A letter out of the
blue from the state pen.

180
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:36,483
It took a long time,

181
00:15:37,350 --> 00:15:39,813
but I finally got up the
courage to write to you.

182
00:15:41,730 --> 00:15:44,163
I read your book of poetry about the sun,

183
00:15:46,230 --> 00:15:48,280
and it just about kept me alive in here

184
00:15:50,040 --> 00:15:51,507
after what happened."

185
00:15:53,958 --> 00:15:57,291
(gentle dramatic music)

186
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:11,551
(waterfall hisses)

187
00:16:15,540 --> 00:16:17,414
- I'll see you next week now. Okay?

188
00:16:17,414 --> 00:16:18,247
- Okay.

189
00:16:21,390 --> 00:16:22,223
- [Penny] Ready?

190
00:16:24,240 --> 00:16:25,410
Why next week?

191
00:16:25,410 --> 00:16:27,270
- Your sister's been a little congested,

192
00:16:27,270 --> 00:16:28,980
in case you hadn't noticed.

193
00:16:28,980 --> 00:16:31,230
I'd like to see her next
week, run some tests.

194
00:16:31,230 --> 00:16:32,780
- What if she's fine next week?

195
00:16:34,710 --> 00:16:37,050
- You know how this disease works.

196
00:16:37,050 --> 00:16:38,670
Do we have to go through this every time?

197
00:16:38,670 --> 00:16:40,110
- Yeah, we do.

198
00:16:40,110 --> 00:16:41,790
This stuff, which is very expensive,

199
00:16:41,790 --> 00:16:43,230
gives her joint pain,

200
00:16:43,230 --> 00:16:45,150
and you run the same tests over and over

201
00:16:45,150 --> 00:16:47,220
and your receptionist
just hassled me again

202
00:16:47,220 --> 00:16:48,510
about her Medicare being screwed up.

203
00:16:48,510 --> 00:16:49,343
- Penny.

204
00:16:53,760 --> 00:16:54,663
- Next week?

205
00:16:56,190 --> 00:16:58,690
- I'm sorry. It's better
when Professor takes you.

206
00:16:59,910 --> 00:17:01,560
- It's more interesting with you.

207
00:17:02,903 --> 00:17:04,353
I think the doctor hates you.

208
00:17:05,257 --> 00:17:06,780
- "Your sister's been a little congested,

209
00:17:06,780 --> 00:17:08,307
in case you hadn't noticed."

210
00:17:11,130 --> 00:17:12,780
- Let's go get this stuff filled.

211
00:17:15,583 --> 00:17:18,330
(bell rings)

212
00:17:18,330 --> 00:17:19,163
- Hello, ladies.

213
00:17:20,190 --> 00:17:21,060
- Hello.

214
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:23,543
- Why don't you get us some
bread while we wait, sweetheart?

215
00:17:26,228 --> 00:17:29,645
(gentle whimsical music)

216
00:17:36,946 --> 00:17:37,779
- Penny.

217
00:17:39,239 --> 00:17:40,290
Penny.

218
00:17:40,290 --> 00:17:41,123
- What?

219
00:17:41,123 --> 00:17:41,956
- Our neighbor.
- Slow down. What neighbor?

220
00:17:41,956 --> 00:17:43,110
- The stock boy is our new
neighbor. Come and see.

221
00:17:43,110 --> 00:17:43,943
- No. No.

222
00:17:58,170 --> 00:17:59,003
- Hello.

223
00:18:01,200 --> 00:18:03,000
My name is Mary. Do you remember me?

224
00:18:05,400 --> 00:18:06,800
I poured water on your head.

225
00:18:11,550 --> 00:18:14,793
We're your neighbors.
Me and my sister, Penny.

226
00:18:16,949 --> 00:18:18,949
- Mary.
- [Mary] Come on.

227
00:18:23,070 --> 00:18:26,073
We'd like to invite you to dinner.

228
00:18:29,730 --> 00:18:32,100
I don't think he speaks English.

229
00:18:32,100 --> 00:18:33,810
- Well, that's rude.

230
00:18:33,810 --> 00:18:34,760
- I speak a little.

231
00:18:37,320 --> 00:18:40,563
- I'd like to apologize
for my sister, the stalker.

232
00:18:42,343 --> 00:18:43,980
- What is a stalker?

233
00:18:43,980 --> 00:18:47,370
- It's when somebody likes
you and you don't like them,

234
00:18:47,370 --> 00:18:48,720
and they follow you around.

235
00:18:51,870 --> 00:18:53,420
So, you'll come to dinner then?

236
00:19:03,089 --> 00:19:06,150
Come at eight o'clock.
We're in apartment three.

237
00:19:06,150 --> 00:19:07,050
- [Penny] Come on.

238
00:19:08,940 --> 00:19:10,337
Prescription's filled.

239
00:19:19,239 --> 00:19:21,489
- Penny, it's almost eight.

240
00:19:26,814 --> 00:19:27,647
Penny.

241
00:19:39,142 --> 00:19:41,735
(Mary coughs)

242
00:19:41,735 --> 00:19:44,235
(eerie music)

243
00:19:51,228 --> 00:19:52,061
Penny.

244
00:19:55,198 --> 00:19:57,698
(pager beeps)

245
00:20:07,277 --> 00:20:09,777
(bag rustles)

246
00:20:15,851 --> 00:20:18,660
- Do you want some dinner before you go?

247
00:20:18,660 --> 00:20:19,743
- [Penny] Not hungry.

248
00:20:48,060 --> 00:20:49,140
- Smells good.

249
00:20:51,223 --> 00:20:52,723
I hope you have a nice dinner.

250
00:20:54,900 --> 00:20:57,000
Maybe tomorrow, I can take you to a movie.

251
00:21:00,810 --> 00:21:02,610
- Why don't you even wanna meet him?

252
00:21:10,853 --> 00:21:13,270
(door shuts)

253
00:21:30,247 --> 00:21:32,830
(gentle music)

254
00:21:59,152 --> 00:22:02,164
(knocking)

255
00:22:02,164 --> 00:22:02,997
- Shoot.

256
00:22:10,651 --> 00:22:12,454
Oh, flowers.

257
00:22:12,454 --> 00:22:13,621
- For you and?

258
00:22:14,486 --> 00:22:17,490
- Penny. Went out.

259
00:22:17,490 --> 00:22:18,323
Come in.

260
00:22:25,948 --> 00:22:28,698
(train rumbling)

261
00:22:30,167 --> 00:22:35,167
♪ Can't wait a minute 'cause
I ain't got the time today ♪

262
00:22:35,310 --> 00:22:37,180
- Well, I'm on the corner of Bethman,

263
00:22:38,130 --> 00:22:39,573
but nobody's here.

264
00:22:41,550 --> 00:22:42,600
All right, I'll wait.

265
00:22:47,199 --> 00:22:52,199
♪ Can't wait for questions
'cause the answers (indistinct) ♪

266
00:22:53,261 --> 00:22:58,261
♪ If I hold on while you make me wait ♪

267
00:22:58,569 --> 00:23:03,569
♪ If I hold on, you know that way ♪

268
00:23:04,244 --> 00:23:08,880
♪ If I hold on, what am I waiting for? ♪

269
00:23:08,880 --> 00:23:11,340
- [Mary] I don't know if
you can tell by meeting her,

270
00:23:11,340 --> 00:23:13,923
but she's a genius.

271
00:23:15,990 --> 00:23:17,253
She wrote a book once.

272
00:23:22,410 --> 00:23:23,913
Do you think I look 16?

273
00:23:26,552 --> 00:23:30,560
I almost am, but I'm afraid
I look three years stunted.

274
00:23:33,840 --> 00:23:36,420
- I like the soup. It's good.

275
00:23:36,420 --> 00:23:38,820
- [Mary] Really? I made
it. It's not from a can.

276
00:23:40,530 --> 00:23:43,590
- [Man] My mother is
making a soup like this.

277
00:23:43,590 --> 00:23:44,423
- Really?

278
00:23:45,990 --> 00:23:47,290
Tell me about your family.

279
00:23:52,020 --> 00:23:55,350
Oh, I just said a faux pas, didn't I?

280
00:23:55,350 --> 00:24:00,330
- No. I don't know where is my family.

281
00:24:00,330 --> 00:24:03,273
My country no longer exists.

282
00:24:04,890 --> 00:24:05,723
- Oh.

283
00:24:10,440 --> 00:24:13,803
- Your sister don't like me, I think.

284
00:24:16,440 --> 00:24:17,763
- She doesn't like anyone.

285
00:24:19,320 --> 00:24:20,153
- Why not?

286
00:24:21,720 --> 00:24:22,683
- Because of me.

287
00:24:29,850 --> 00:24:34,323
- [Man] I know this probably
seems crazy, maybe even scary.

288
00:24:35,310 --> 00:24:38,760
But I finally got up the
courage to write to you.

289
00:24:38,760 --> 00:24:40,563
Your poem, To Mary.

290
00:24:41,784 --> 00:24:44,820
(gentle whimsical music)

291
00:24:44,820 --> 00:24:46,200
When I first read it,

292
00:24:46,200 --> 00:24:48,333
I felt like I was breaking on the inside.

293
00:24:49,170 --> 00:24:52,110
It was somebody who
knew what I was feeling.

294
00:24:52,110 --> 00:24:55,320
Somebody who knew what it's
like to lose everything.

295
00:24:55,320 --> 00:24:57,180
When I finished reading your book,

296
00:24:57,180 --> 00:24:59,400
I just had to write you and thank you,

297
00:25:01,440 --> 00:25:03,954
because it's just about
kept me alive in here.

298
00:25:03,954 --> 00:25:06,704
(car horn beeps)

299
00:25:13,633 --> 00:25:15,330
- [Mary] I'm not sad.

300
00:25:15,330 --> 00:25:17,940
I still have this great
belief that exciting things

301
00:25:17,940 --> 00:25:19,710
are going to happen to me.

302
00:25:19,710 --> 00:25:21,243
Scandalous things.

303
00:25:22,410 --> 00:25:25,500
- Is this why you ask me, "Do I look 16?"

304
00:25:25,500 --> 00:25:27,903
- Well, do I? I do, don't I?

305
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:42,543
Penny remembers things from before.

306
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:45,453
Things I don't.

307
00:25:50,490 --> 00:25:52,440
When our parents were alive,

308
00:25:52,440 --> 00:25:57,420
we lived in this house with
stilts, right on the beach.

309
00:25:57,420 --> 00:25:58,293
- Stilts?

310
00:25:59,970 --> 00:26:01,383
- Like legs.

311
00:26:05,190 --> 00:26:07,390
Penny's gonna take me
there for my birthday.

312
00:26:09,120 --> 00:26:11,793
- And after the house with the legs?

313
00:26:17,400 --> 00:26:18,663
- After the accident,

314
00:26:22,020 --> 00:26:23,370
we stayed with a foster family,

315
00:26:23,370 --> 00:26:26,283
but we didn't live with them very long.

316
00:26:28,380 --> 00:26:29,850
And we had money from our parents,

317
00:26:29,850 --> 00:26:32,790
and we had money from the book.

318
00:26:32,790 --> 00:26:36,513
And then it all ran out.

319
00:26:38,070 --> 00:26:40,820
- [Man] And now, no more books?

320
00:26:46,083 --> 00:26:48,963
- [Mary] It's funny what
you say about your country,

321
00:26:50,010 --> 00:26:51,483
how it doesn't exist.

322
00:26:53,040 --> 00:26:55,090
It's kind of like that with me and Penny.

323
00:27:00,562 --> 00:27:03,145
(somber music)

324
00:27:07,853 --> 00:27:10,635
(train rumbling)

325
00:27:10,635 --> 00:27:13,218
(mellow music)

326
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:20,153
- [Man] What are you doing in there?

327
00:27:26,550 --> 00:27:27,383
Come on.

328
00:27:36,840 --> 00:27:38,130
- [Mary] I never remember anything

329
00:27:38,130 --> 00:27:39,963
besides beginnings and endings.

330
00:27:41,070 --> 00:27:44,430
Why is it that the ending's
the most beautiful part?

331
00:27:44,430 --> 00:27:45,483
- Because it's fake.

332
00:27:47,310 --> 00:27:48,213
Did you like it?

333
00:27:49,200 --> 00:27:50,033
- Yes.

334
00:27:51,570 --> 00:27:53,320
- So, does this make up for dinner?

335
00:27:55,110 --> 00:27:55,943
- Sure.

336
00:28:00,300 --> 00:28:03,363
- So, how was dinner anyway?

337
00:28:04,530 --> 00:28:06,150
- All right.

338
00:28:06,150 --> 00:28:07,680
- Hmm?

339
00:28:07,680 --> 00:28:09,380
- I think you'd like him. He's 22.

340
00:28:10,290 --> 00:28:12,140
- You're obsessed with people's ages.

341
00:28:14,460 --> 00:28:16,960
(Mary coughs)

342
00:28:22,817 --> 00:28:25,317
(bus rumbles)

343
00:28:26,490 --> 00:28:30,840
Mary, why did you put that
convict's letter in my purse?

344
00:28:30,840 --> 00:28:32,400
- He's appealing.

345
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:34,710
- Appealing what? A life sentence.

346
00:28:34,710 --> 00:28:36,060
- Don't tell me it didn't flatter you

347
00:28:36,060 --> 00:28:37,020
that he liked your book.

348
00:28:37,020 --> 00:28:37,863
- Please.

349
00:28:39,480 --> 00:28:41,040
- His favorite poem was the one to me.

350
00:28:41,040 --> 00:28:42,090
Did you read that part?

351
00:28:42,090 --> 00:28:44,130
- No, I didn't read a word of it.

352
00:28:44,130 --> 00:28:46,590
You like him so much, you write to him.

353
00:28:46,590 --> 00:28:48,990
Or don't. He's probably a rapist.

354
00:28:48,990 --> 00:28:50,463
- Wait. Don't throw it away.

355
00:28:54,711 --> 00:28:55,544
- You okay?

356
00:28:58,380 --> 00:28:59,213
Mary?

357
00:29:03,186 --> 00:29:05,686
(Mary coughs)

358
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:09,890
- We didn't have to go out, you know?

359
00:29:10,995 --> 00:29:11,828
- I'm fine.

360
00:29:11,828 --> 00:29:13,950
- Look at you. You have
a fever. Look at you.

361
00:29:15,330 --> 00:29:16,163
- Look at you.

362
00:29:20,280 --> 00:29:21,810
- It's good.

363
00:29:21,810 --> 00:29:22,760
Just a little more.

364
00:29:26,386 --> 00:29:27,842
Good.

365
00:29:27,842 --> 00:29:30,425
(somber music)

366
00:29:39,265 --> 00:29:41,765
(man snoring)

367
00:29:46,410 --> 00:29:47,243
- Smoke?

368
00:29:49,080 --> 00:29:50,030
- It isn't allowed.

369
00:29:51,090 --> 00:29:52,920
- What's he gonna do? He's my uncle.

370
00:29:52,920 --> 00:29:54,633
Besides, he's in a coma out there.

371
00:29:57,840 --> 00:29:59,853
So, how you doing? Is the job okay?

372
00:30:01,932 --> 00:30:06,000
- I have an apartment not
far, and I've made a friend.

373
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:06,833
- Good.

374
00:30:12,361 --> 00:30:15,410
- Have you been reading the news?

375
00:30:15,410 --> 00:30:17,940
More the same. All hell's
breaking loose in the south.

376
00:30:17,940 --> 00:30:19,143
Some ceasefire.

377
00:30:23,970 --> 00:30:25,290
There hasn't been anything for you yet.

378
00:30:25,290 --> 00:30:27,540
If I get a letter, I'll
run my ass over here.

379
00:30:30,840 --> 00:30:34,980
- [Mary] Dear Samuel, thank
you for your brilliant letter.

380
00:30:34,980 --> 00:30:37,833
Every poet loves praise, especially me.

381
00:30:39,060 --> 00:30:42,120
And you are so kind to
ask after my sister Mary.

382
00:30:42,120 --> 00:30:44,820
She's such a beautiful girl,

383
00:30:44,820 --> 00:30:46,980
and talented.

384
00:30:46,980 --> 00:30:51,980
And she's very mature for her age.

385
00:30:53,580 --> 00:30:56,933
I hope this can be a start of
a brilliant correspondence.

386
00:31:02,490 --> 00:31:03,963
Sincerely.

387
00:31:05,580 --> 00:31:06,413
No.

388
00:31:10,260 --> 00:31:13,263
Your friend and confidante, Penny.

389
00:31:14,501 --> 00:31:17,918
(gentle whimsical music)

390
00:31:37,570 --> 00:31:40,237
(muffled music)

391
00:32:18,810 --> 00:32:20,400
- [Penny] Your parents went to Florida,

392
00:32:20,400 --> 00:32:22,593
and all you got was this lousy shirt.

393
00:32:23,970 --> 00:32:26,883
- No, my friend gave it to me.

394
00:32:30,960 --> 00:32:32,940
I came to see Mary.

395
00:32:32,940 --> 00:32:36,222
- Oh, well she's been sick. She's asleep.

396
00:32:36,222 --> 00:32:38,359
- [Mary] Penny, I'm getting up.

397
00:32:38,359 --> 00:32:39,783
I'm getting up.

398
00:32:39,783 --> 00:32:42,813
- Well in that case, come on in.

399
00:32:44,940 --> 00:32:47,913
- [Mary] This is Penny's
page. That's her hand.

400
00:32:49,716 --> 00:32:52,216
(Mary coughs)

401
00:32:54,353 --> 00:32:55,201
- [Man] What is it?

402
00:32:55,201 --> 00:32:58,860
- [Mary] An angel. More stars.

403
00:32:58,860 --> 00:33:03,363
Miss Mary Mac. Stuff.
Buttons, butterflies.

404
00:33:05,070 --> 00:33:08,910
Can I hear something in your language?

405
00:33:08,910 --> 00:33:09,910
- What should I say?

406
00:33:11,949 --> 00:33:13,971
- I don't know.

407
00:33:13,971 --> 00:33:15,971
How about, "I love you"?

408
00:33:22,013 --> 00:33:23,346
- I love you is.

409
00:33:24,310 --> 00:33:26,105
(man speaks foreign language)

410
00:33:26,105 --> 00:33:27,272
- That's nice.

411
00:33:31,043 --> 00:33:32,633
- I'm gonna get something to drink.

412
00:33:36,540 --> 00:33:38,490
- [Mary] And this is my astronaut page.

413
00:33:39,450 --> 00:33:41,050
Do you know about the astronaut?

414
00:33:42,480 --> 00:33:44,100
He's all alone up in space.

415
00:33:44,100 --> 00:33:46,943
- It's quite nice. Be close to the stars.

416
00:33:51,687 --> 00:33:52,620
- No, it's sad.

417
00:33:52,620 --> 00:33:53,910
If he can't fix his ship,

418
00:33:53,910 --> 00:33:55,440
he'll be lost for a billion years,

419
00:33:55,440 --> 00:33:57,453
and the sun will burn him up.

420
00:34:00,150 --> 00:34:03,187
- [Man] Do you only put
sad things in your book?

421
00:34:04,620 --> 00:34:07,323
- No, not just sad.

422
00:34:09,150 --> 00:34:11,283
It's my book of beautiful things.

423
00:34:13,110 --> 00:34:14,820
- Hey, yeah, you're in here.

424
00:34:14,820 --> 00:34:15,810
- [Mary] Penny.

425
00:34:15,810 --> 00:34:17,130
- [Penny] She cut out her old boyfriend

426
00:34:17,130 --> 00:34:18,210
and replaced him with you.

427
00:34:18,210 --> 00:34:19,043
See?

428
00:34:22,358 --> 00:34:24,191
- Why did you do that?

429
00:34:26,704 --> 00:34:28,204
- It is beautiful.

430
00:34:43,153 --> 00:34:46,570
(gentle whimsical music)

431
00:34:47,733 --> 00:34:50,460
- [Samuel] It's strange to
think I've never met you,

432
00:34:50,460 --> 00:34:54,000
but there are pieces of you, these poems,

433
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:54,873
I know by heart.

434
00:34:56,977 --> 00:34:59,640
"Just when life seemed to matter little,

435
00:34:59,640 --> 00:35:01,540
you braved my heart's eclipse

436
00:35:03,028 --> 00:35:04,428
to bathe me with your light.

437
00:35:06,090 --> 00:35:08,880
A thousand different yesterdays

438
00:35:08,880 --> 00:35:10,533
could have left me all alone.

439
00:35:12,150 --> 00:35:14,880
A thousand different yesterdays

440
00:35:14,880 --> 00:35:18,033
would not have left me
bleeding where you touched me.

441
00:35:18,960 --> 00:35:21,153
Lost in the maze of our imagining.

442
00:35:22,020 --> 00:35:24,900
Lost in the harsh glare of forgetting.

443
00:35:24,900 --> 00:35:28,907
The sun, which is always
rising, is always setting."

444
00:35:34,233 --> 00:35:37,066
(distant traffic)

445
00:35:49,860 --> 00:35:50,984
- [Professor] Listen to me.

446
00:35:50,984 --> 00:35:51,817
- [Penny] No.

447
00:35:51,817 --> 00:35:52,650
- [Professor] All it is, listen to me.

448
00:35:52,650 --> 00:35:55,017
All it is is a form that you have to sign.

449
00:35:55,017 --> 00:35:55,980
- [Penny] No, no hospital.

450
00:35:55,980 --> 00:35:57,660
- Her lungs are damaged, Penny.

451
00:35:57,660 --> 00:35:59,880
You knew it would come
to this, eventually.

452
00:35:59,880 --> 00:36:01,410
- Yeah, well, I can't deal
with any more hospitals.

453
00:36:01,410 --> 00:36:02,243
- [Professor] You can't deal with them.

454
00:36:02,243 --> 00:36:04,050
You, who won't even
take her to the clinic.

455
00:36:04,050 --> 00:36:05,580
- [Penny] I take her to the clinic.

456
00:36:05,580 --> 00:36:07,230
I just don't see the point anymore.

457
00:36:07,230 --> 00:36:08,760
- [Professor] Well, we're
going to have to learn

458
00:36:08,760 --> 00:36:10,590
to see the point because
this is the reality

459
00:36:10,590 --> 00:36:11,640
that we are faced with.

460
00:36:11,640 --> 00:36:13,710
- Well, why can't they
treat her with antibiotics?

461
00:36:13,710 --> 00:36:15,660
- [Professor] Because the
antibiotics don't work anymore.

462
00:36:15,660 --> 00:36:16,950
- [Mary] Please stop it, you guys.

463
00:36:16,950 --> 00:36:18,150
- [Penny] How do you know
they're not gonna work?

464
00:36:18,150 --> 00:36:19,440
What are you, a doctor all of a sudden?

465
00:36:19,440 --> 00:36:20,273
- [Professor] No, I'm not a doctor,

466
00:36:20,273 --> 00:36:21,570
but I'm the one that spends all my time

467
00:36:21,570 --> 00:36:22,440
speaking to the doctors,

468
00:36:22,440 --> 00:36:24,330
and I think I should have some say

469
00:36:24,330 --> 00:36:25,170
in your sister's treatment,

470
00:36:25,170 --> 00:36:27,060
because I am the one that
has to be responsible

471
00:36:27,060 --> 00:36:27,893
for most of it.

472
00:36:27,893 --> 00:36:28,726
- [Penny] What do you want from me?

473
00:36:28,726 --> 00:36:29,820
You want me to tell you what a worthy,

474
00:36:29,820 --> 00:36:31,440
valuable human being you are?

475
00:36:31,440 --> 00:36:33,150
Fine. I'd be happy to do that.

476
00:36:33,150 --> 00:36:35,400
- This is not about me.
And it's not about you.

477
00:36:35,400 --> 00:36:36,720
- This is about you.

478
00:36:36,720 --> 00:36:39,873
You love to play savior, you
know, but you're not God.

479
00:36:40,740 --> 00:36:43,350
You're just a lonely, irrelevant man

480
00:36:43,350 --> 00:36:45,237
who has no one to take care of.

481
00:36:45,237 --> 00:36:46,470
- [Professor] No, no one,

482
00:36:46,470 --> 00:36:48,660
except a very, very sick little girl

483
00:36:48,660 --> 00:36:51,210
with a prostitute dope fiend for a sister,

484
00:36:51,210 --> 00:36:52,230
who doesn't have the guts,

485
00:36:52,230 --> 00:36:54,066
because she's too busy dealing with Johns-

486
00:36:54,066 --> 00:36:55,287
- Don't call her that.
- In the street.

487
00:36:55,287 --> 00:36:58,740
You never think about her,
always about yourself.

488
00:36:58,740 --> 00:37:00,120
It's never what Mary needs.

489
00:37:00,120 --> 00:37:02,583
- I need for you guys to stop.

490
00:37:07,576 --> 00:37:10,159
(somber music)

491
00:37:21,531 --> 00:37:22,364
- Penny?

492
00:37:51,990 --> 00:37:55,593
- I'm not gonna let them
stick knives and tubes in her,

493
00:37:58,740 --> 00:38:01,203
when we all know it won't do any good.

494
00:38:03,780 --> 00:38:05,647
I'll never let them do that to her.

495
00:38:07,764 --> 00:38:11,200
- [Man] She told me she was sick.

496
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:12,390
- [Penny] Well, did she tell you

497
00:38:12,390 --> 00:38:14,890
they want to cut up her
lung, take part of it out?

498
00:38:21,990 --> 00:38:23,240
What do you want from me?

499
00:38:41,764 --> 00:38:44,847
- We used to call it sister fibrosis.

500
00:38:46,830 --> 00:38:49,330
That's how she used to say
it when she was little.

501
00:38:50,850 --> 00:38:52,653
We thought it was for sisters.

502
00:39:00,090 --> 00:39:03,663
You play that music at night, don't you?

503
00:39:09,030 --> 00:39:09,863
- Yes.

504
00:39:12,540 --> 00:39:15,303
And you, every night?

505
00:39:20,070 --> 00:39:21,093
- Not every night.

506
00:39:26,562 --> 00:39:30,390
- Try to feel?

507
00:39:33,240 --> 00:39:35,043
- Oh no, I don't feel a thing.

508
00:39:39,578 --> 00:39:43,661
I don't know why I'm
sitting here talking to you.

509
00:39:48,750 --> 00:39:51,123
- I'm sorry if I'm a stalker.

510
00:39:55,620 --> 00:39:56,453
- Wait.

511
00:40:02,670 --> 00:40:06,273
We'll talk again sometime.

512
00:40:09,330 --> 00:40:10,163
Okay?

513
00:40:24,599 --> 00:40:28,429
- [Mary] I don't wanna go to the hospital.

514
00:40:28,429 --> 00:40:29,467
(gentle music)

515
00:40:29,467 --> 00:40:30,300
- Okay.

516
00:40:35,097 --> 00:40:36,993
- Tell me again about the beach.

517
00:40:46,650 --> 00:40:50,853
- We lived there all year
round with mom and dad.

518
00:40:52,770 --> 00:40:57,030
In the winter, the beach
was completely empty,

519
00:40:57,030 --> 00:40:58,930
and you and I had it all to ourselves.

520
00:41:00,076 --> 00:41:03,723
It felt like infinity.

521
00:41:06,300 --> 00:41:07,700
You'll see when we go there.

522
00:41:12,420 --> 00:41:15,603
- Penny, is it true what Professor said?

523
00:41:18,960 --> 00:41:19,810
- No, sweetheart.

524
00:41:21,990 --> 00:41:22,823
No.

525
00:41:24,480 --> 00:41:29,480
- Well, maybe you could
find a job closer to home.

526
00:41:33,060 --> 00:41:33,893
- Maybe.

527
00:41:37,500 --> 00:41:41,313
- Don't go out tonight. Stay here with me.

528
00:41:45,060 --> 00:41:47,583
Hold still. I'm almost done.

529
00:41:51,148 --> 00:41:54,547
- What do you think? It's beautiful.

530
00:41:54,547 --> 00:41:56,595
- You're an ugly frowning face.

531
00:41:56,595 --> 00:41:57,428
- Shut up.

